<HEADLINE>
FT  29 NOV 93 / UK Company News: Stagecoach pays Pounds 9m for Western
Travel
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHARLES BATCHELOR, Transport Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Stagecoach, the operator of regional bus services, is to buy Western Travel,
another bus company, for Pounds 9.25m, in a deal which brings to three the
number of acquisitions since Stagecoach was floated in April.
To finance the purchase, Stagecoach will issue 3m new shares valued at
Pounds 4.75m, Pounds 4m worth of loan notes and pay Pounds 500,000 in cash.
In addition it will lend Western Travel Pounds 2.1m to part-finance the
payment of a special dividend of Pounds 4.5m to the vendors.
Western Travel made a pre-tax profit of Pounds 1.86m on turnover of Pounds
33.9m in 1992. It had net assets of Pounds 6.5m at that date. The company
operates 650 buses and employs 1,700 people.
Western Travel takes Stagecoach, which is based in Perth, into three new
geographical areas.
Its C&amp;G subsidiary operates in Cheltenham, Gloucester, Swindon and Stroud;
Midland Red (South) is in Warwick-shire and north Oxfordshire, while Red and
White Services operates in rural South Wales.
