<HEADLINE>
FT  29 NOV 93 / Company News (This Week): Investors hope to strike lucky on
dividend - Hanson
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
With the US coal strike apparently moving towards a settlement, Hanson may
have some good news for its shareholders when it reports annual profits on
Thursday.
The strike cost Hanson Pounds 29m in the third quarter and it predicted it
would cost Pounds 60m-Pounds 80m in the fourth, to the end of September, so
the total cost could be Pounds 100m for the year. Investors are keen to see
a settlement, the only question is what the coal producers will have had to
give to the mineworkers to achieve that.
The market is also hoping for a dividend increase, although forecasts are
for a fall in pre-tax profits from Pounds 1.29bn (FRS3 basis) in 1992 to
Pounds 1.05bn-Pounds 1.07bn, and around Pounds 50m less excluding disposal
profits against Pounds 1.09bn. Either way earnings per share will be
significantly lower.
Hanson pays its dividends quarterly, and has paid 2.85p for each of the last
four payments. Some feel an increase is due, perhaps to 3p a quarter, while
others think a rise will not be forthcoming.
Another concern is the level of gearing following the Dollars 3.2bn (Pounds
2.1bn) purchase of Quantum Chemical, which went through on the last day of
the financial year. Gearing could top 80 per cent, depending on provisions
and asset revaluations. Underlying cash flow is not expected to be strong
enough to make a sizeable dent in the debt in the short term.
This explains Hanson's current drive to make disposals. After last week's
two deals worth Pounds 166m, there may be more news. The City will no doubt
read into the disposals something more about Hanson's future strategy. It
may also hope for further hints on management succession following the
recent promotion of Mr Derek Bonham, chief executive, to the title of deputy
chairman apparently making him front runner to succeed Lord Hanson when he
retires in 1997.
</TEXT>
