<HEADLINE>
FT  29 NOV 93 / 'I am not a conman, I am a very capable salesman'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL ABRAHAMS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Roger Levitt, former chairman of the collapsed Levitt Group, yesterday
emerged after a lunch of hot salt beef and chips from his wife's house in St
John's Wood, London, to express his joy about the 180 hours of community
service given him last week.
'I am absolutely delighted to be free. This is the first day with my family
when we feel a little bit of security. They have got their dad home for
Christmas and I am very pleased to be with them,' he said. In December 1990,
Mr Levitt filed for personal bankruptcy and his financial services group
collapsed with debts of Pounds 34m.
When asked whether the sentence was too lenient - the offence for which he
pleaded guilty carries a maximum sentence of seven years' imprisonment - he
said the result of the court case spoke for itself.
'If the judge and prosecution thought I should have gone to prison, I guess
that is what would have happened. The judge and prosecution were marvellous.
They are nice people and justice was seen to be done,' he said.
'I am not a conman, I am a very capable salesman,' Mr Levitt added. 'I was
most unlucky to lose a Pounds 150m business.'
Last week, eight days into his Old Bailey trial, Mr Levitt unexpectedly
pleaded guilty to a charge of fraudulent trading. The Serious Fraud Office
had in return agreed not to proceed with 21 other charges, including false
accounting, forgery and obtaining property and services by deception.
Mr Levitt said his probation officer had scheduled a meeting with community
services for tomorrow. 'I will do whatever is required of me. With a strong
heart, I will endeavour to do my best and show my decency to society. I
shall enjoy helping the youth of the country. I shall do more than 180
hours. I have always been very charitable.'
As for the future, he said he was looking at various areas of business. 'You
can be assured I will be back in business.'
Mr Levitt added that he had received a great deal of public support. 'Once
the verdict went in my favour, it was amazing how many friends came out of
the woodwork to say 'Well done Roger'.'
</TEXT>
