<HEADLINE>
FT  29 NOV 93 / Budget 1993: Reduction in interest rates demanded
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN WILLMAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
More than 70 of a panel of 100 top businessmen, industrialists, politicians
and other opinion formers want reductions in interest rates, with
three-quarters seeking a cut of 1 percentage point or more, John Willman
writes. Interest rates fell 0.5 percentage point last week.
The opinion formers, polled regularly by Opinion Leader Research, are
overwhelmingly against Budget increases in income tax or value added tax.
They are also opposed to extensions in the scope of VAT, but there is
support for reducing or abolishing mortgage interest tax relief.
There is comfort for the chancellor in the panel's growing optimism in the
economic situation. Sixty nine expect the economy to improve in the next 12
months. A year ago just 48 of the panel were optimistic. And 73 believe that
the economy has improved in the past 12 months, compared with one a year
ago. A quarter believe that the government's policies are the right ones for
the economy. But two-thirds believe that there has been no 'economic
miracle' in recent years, and that the British economy is no stronger than
it used to be.
</TEXT>
