<HEADLINE>
FT  29 NOV 93 / Redwood hits back on valleys renewal drive
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROLAND ADBURGHAM, Wales and West Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr John Redwood, Welsh secretary, has strongly defended the government
initiative to regenerate the south Wales valleys after last week's official
report which cast doubt on the success of its efforts to create jobs.
He said: 'I think that without the initiative the valleys would have been
much worse off.'
The report published by the Government Statistical Service said
manufacturing jobs created had been more than offset by job losses, and that
more factories had closed than had opened.
The initiative was launched in 1988 by Lord Walker, then Welsh secretary,
and who now chairs the regeneration agency English Partnerships. Public
funding totalling Pounds 773m has been spent on the Welsh initiative, and a
second five-year programme was launched this year.
Mr Redwood said the figures concealed the impact of the recession. He said:
'In the recession the valleys performed relatively very well. Had we been in
boom conditions, I think we would have seen very strong positive advances in
the valleys.'
The valleys programme has been criticised as a marketing exercise
encompassing projects such as land reclamation and house renovation which
might have taken place anyway and with little additional funding. But Mr
Redwood described marketing as vital.
'It was very important to try to lift the image of the valleys, both within
the valleys themselves to encourage more self-help and to the outside world
to persuade new investors that this was a beautiful part of Wales with a
future, and not just a scarred piece of Wales with a past that had gone
wrong,' he said.
Mr Redwood emphasised the need for private-sector investment but said he
supported intervention by the government in such severe circumstances.
He said: 'I think it is quite reasonable for government to spend money to
take action when some or all of the problems have been aided or abetted by
public-sector activity. In the valleys it was the rapid decline of
nationalised industries which had created the unemployment and left enormous
scars on the landscape.
'I was a strong supporter of the valleys initiative at the time (it was
launched), although people will now try to claim that the leopard has
changed his spots.'
Mr Redwood accused Labour of attacking the initiative from contradictory
standpoints. He said: 'They're both arguing that the expenditure of these
large sums of public money hasn't done any good, and they're arguing that we
ought to spend a lot more.' The valleys had done 'extremely well' in terms
of relative government funding.
</TEXT>
