<HEADLINE>
FT  29 NOV 93 / Budget 1993: Clarke regime gives mandarins more time for
lunch - Peter Marsh explains how the chancellor's relaxed approach has won
him friends at the Treasury
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MARSH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Asked about how life has changed since Mr Kenneth Clarke took over as
chancellor, the Treasury mandarin patted his stomach. Even with the strains
of preparing the first Budget covering both tax and spending, top officials
have found more time for lunch.
They have taken their cue from Mr Clarke, who has brought a new air of
self-confidence to a government department heavily criticised for economic
policy mistakes in recent years.
A government official said: 'Clarke has been good for the Treasury. He has a
view about everything and has refused to get bogged down in economic jargon.
Unlike (former chancellor) Norman Lamont, who identified with the Treasury,
Clarke really does not care about the place as an institution. The
relationship is healthier.'
Since replacing Mr Lamont six months ago Mr Clarke has abandoned the
Treasury tradition of barely talking to the outside world in the pre-Budget
period.
One former Treasury official witnessed Mr Clarke earlier this month discuss
at a City lunch the possibility of imposing extra taxes on pension funds in
tomorrow's Budget. He said: 'It took my breath away to see the chancellor
discussing potential victims, rather than hide from sight.'
While morale at the Treasury has been helped by signs of economic recovery
after the traumas of the recession and sterling's devaluation, another
important factor has been Mr Clarke's personality. A government official
said: 'People talk about Clarke as a future prime minister. This is bound to
affect the confidence of the people working for him.'
Another official said: 'He's better at reading his briefs than Mr Lamont and
better organised.' This means fewer set-piece meetings in the chancellor's
office to talk about such issues as monetary policy or European affairs.
While Mr Lamont often called two such meetings a day, each of them involving
up to 10 officials whose workloads were consequently stretched, Mr Clarke
makes do with about two a week.
The generally positive view about the chancellor - a political heavyweight
who came to the Treasury after a succession of cabinet jobs including home
secretary and secretary for health and education - is shared by several
outside the department.
Mr James Bruxner, chairman of the Scotch Whisky Association, which has
regular contacts with the Treasury, said of a recent meeting with Mr Clarke
about the Budget: 'Unlike Mr Lamont, who played his cards very close to his
chest, Mr Clarke came across as eager to have a dialogue.'
Mr Clarke appears to be attracted by the political rather than the technical
aspects of the chancellor's job. One person who talked to him recently about
the Budget said: 'His eyes flashed when I suggested he could pull off a coup
by increasing taxes now, only to bring them down again later in what could
be a vote winner ahead of a 1997 election.'
Some believe Mr Clarke has not done enough to get on top of economic issues.
He has left such details to two of his top civil servants - Sir Terry Burns,
Treasury permanent secretary, and Mr Alan Budd, the department's chief
economic adviser - with whom he has struck a friendly though not
particularly close relationship.
One person close to the Treasury said: 'My fear is that he does not know
enough (about economics) and that at some point this could trip him up.'
On broad political questions the chancellor relies on Mrs Tessa Keswick, his
political adviser at the Treasury, who worked for him at his other cabinet
positions.
Mrs Keswick is a former Conservative councillor in the London borough of
Kensington and Chelsea, and sister-in-law of Sir 'Chips' Keswick, chairman
of Hambros Bank. She is fiercely protective of Mr Clarke and fond of
referring to him as 'my man'. One insider says of Mrs Keswick: 'She's a
sensible middle-aged lady who has a good political feel.'
Not everyone at the Treasury has a wholly positive view of Mr Clarke. Some
officials concerned with public spending and economics are said to have been
put out after being subjected to 'aggressive' questioning from the
chancellor. One person close to him said: 'Clarke can be brusque but he's
hardly ever malicious. He's used to getting into a new department and asking
enough questions until he's on top of his brief.'
</TEXT>
