<HEADLINE>
FT  29 NOV 93 / Apprentice scheme expected
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LISA WOOD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
An apprenticeship scheme for people aged from 16 to 19 is expected to be
suggested by the chancellor in the Budget tomorrow, Lisa Wood writes.
The scheme would replace Youth Training and would aim to give qualifications
up to the National Vocational Qualification level three, which is a
crafts-level qualification. At present most YT students aim for NVQ level
two.
Funding for the scheme would be related to the acquisition of skills.
Youth Training has had a poor image among participants and employers.
Growing numbers of young people are preferring to remain at school or
college rather than join YT.
The Department of Employment's Pounds 1.8bn training programme is likely to
be cut in the Budget, with schemes catering for unemployed adults believed
to be vulnerable.
