<HEADLINE>
FT  29 NOV 93 / Catering deals elude private sector
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Compulsory competitive tendering of catering has failed to have much impact,
with only 6 per cent of contracts put out to tender being awarded to private
contractors.
A report from the Institute of Public Finance shows that local authority
contracts form only 1.4 per cent of the Pounds 2.4bn contract-catering
market.
No great savings have been made for the public, with a 1.5 per cent increase
in expenditure on education and welfare catering since compulsory
competitive tendering was introduced. Some counties have raised school-meal
charges and others are phasing them out.
The catering industry accepts that the Transfer of Undertakings (Public
Employees) regulations (Tupe) apply to council catering contracts. This
means that employees must be offered jobs on their existing terms and
con-ditions, and most con-tractors are tendering on this basis.
But the institute said that opportunities for the private sector would
increase because of the introduction of local management in schools.
It said the high cost of taking over county council school-meals budgets -
the average annual contract is Pounds 1.8m - barred most contract caterers.
Of the 2,500 UK contract-catering companies, 62 per cent have an annual
turnover of less than Pounds 100,000.
Eating Out. IPF, Suffolk House, College Road, Croydon CR0 1PF. Pounds 100
(Pounds 50 for local authorities).
</TEXT>
