<HEADLINE>
FT  29 NOV 93 / More than a conduit, insists Adams: Adams calls Mayhew a
liar
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Sinn Fein yesterday rejected the British government's contention that secret
contacts with Sinn Fein had been made through intermediaries in response to
an IRA wish to end the conflict.
Mr Gerry Adams, the Sinn Fein president, said at a news conference in West
Belfast yesterday that the contact amounted to 'more than a mere conduit'.
He said that meetings had been approved by Mr Major, were known about at
cabinet level, and involved several senior civil servants.
Mr Adams disputed Sir Patrick Mayhew's explanation that the IRA had
considered the conflict over. He said: 'At no point was there any
communication from the IRA that the conflict was over.'
Mr Adams accused Sir Patrick of lying about the contacts between the
government and Sinn Fein. He said outlines of policy had been exchanged and
discussed. He indicated that he was preparing to publish material exchanged
between the two sides, saying that it was of the utmost importance to point
out that the issue of talking to Sinn Fein was a distraction. Talks at this
time were not necessary to move towards a lasting peace.
'This required the British government to fulfil its responsibilities. John
Major knows what he needs to do. He knows that the Irish peace initiative
deals with the substantive issues and includes the principles, the dynamic
and the process required to bring peace to Ireland. To use the words of John
Hume, 'Mr Major holds the key'.'
Mr Adams said the government was only interested in protecting its own
position and that Mr Major had no serious interest in conceding to the Irish
people their right to a peaceful future.
He insisted the contact was between Sinn Fein and the government and not the
IRA and the government.
He confirmed it pre-dated February but said, contrary to what Sir Patrick
Mayhew said: 'This particular phase of the contact was initiated by the
British government. Mayhew is telling lies from beginning to end.'
He said Sir Patrick and Mr Major had denied knowing anything that was in the
Hume-Adams initiative, denied on numerous occasions that there were any
contacts at all between the government and Sinn Fein and insisted there
could be no contact without pre-conditions while they were at the same time
actively engaged in contacts.
'The record shows quite clearly all of these things are lies and are proved
to be lies.'
Mr Adams added: 'They have lied to their own parliament, to James Molyneaux
(Ulster Unionist party leader), and to the Irish and British people about
the existence and nature of their contact with Sinn Fein.'
He said the government had for some time set its face against a real peace
process. It had refused to make the change of policy required to 'move all
of us forward into a negotiated settlement. In the course of our contact
with their representatives they rejected and walked away from a peace
process'.
A Sinn Fein spokeswoman said yesterday, however: 'The main point is not
about who said what and when. This is a distraction from the main goal of
laying a basis for getting this war over and done with.'
</TEXT>
