<HEADLINE>
FT  29 NOV 93 / Budget plan for sale of 70,000 defence homes
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS, Political Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Malcolm Rifkind, the defence secretary, plans to sell off nearly 70,000
houses occupied by armed forces personnel to offset the deep cuts imposed by
the Treasury in the Pounds 23bn defence budget.
The scheme, due to be announced as part of the Budget tomorrow, is expected
to raise about Pounds 500m in the financial year beginning April 1995 and
will go into current spending on the defence budget.
Mr Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor, is expected by City economists to
increase taxes by up to Pounds 2bn from next April, on top of the Pounds
6.7bn already announced. He may also announce cuts of Pounds 1bn-Pounds 2bn
in the Treasury's previously published Pounds 254bn control total for public
spending in 1994-95. The chancellor's main preoccupation will be to reduce
the Pounds 50bn fiscal deficit without jeopardising signs of economic
recovery.
The services housing sales are seen by ministers as a crucial element in
attempts to fight off a threatened rebellion by backbench Tory MPs over the
scale of forthcoming defence cuts.
The scheme also marks the start of a wave of new asset sales planned by
Whitehall departments to square the circle of the sharpest squeeze for a
decade on public spending with commitments to preserve crucial budgets.
But the Treasury's approval for Mr Rifkind's plan to plough back the
receipts into current spending on the defence budget has sparked resentment
among other senior ministers.
Mr John Gummer, the environment secretary, has protested that local
authorities which transfer their housing stock to private sector housing
associations are not given similar freedom to spend the receipts.
Mr Rifkind's scheme centres on nearly 70,000 'married quarters' properties
in Britain occupied by defence personnel. More than half - around 35,000 -
are owned by the army, with the air force accounting for about 25,000 and
the navy about 10,000.
Under the proposals, the properties will be transferred via a non-profit
trust to housing associations, building societies and other interested
groups.
Purchasers will be granted a long lease, probably 99 years, on the
properties, which will be occupied by service families at rents determined
by the Armed Services Pay Review Body.
Potential buyers will be able to finance the relatively cheap leases through
guaranteed rents from reliable tenants.
Separately the defence ministry is selling off housing left vacant by the
run-down in the size of the armed forces. Over 4,000 properties have been
sold outright under that scheme.
Clarke regime gives mandarins more time for lunch, Page 6
Voters' demands, Page 7
Lex, Page 18
Economics Notebook, Page 21
