<HEADLINE>
FT  27 NOV 93 / City anger at community service order for Levitt: Judge says
sentence is 'commensurate' - SFO denies error over plea bargain
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN MASON, Law Courts Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Serious Fraud Office was at the centre of another controversy yesterday
when Mr Roger Levitt, the former financial services salesman who pleaded
guilty to fraud after his company collapsed with losses of Pounds 34m,
walked free from court.
Mr Levitt, who headed one of the most successful financial services
companies of the mid-1980s, was ordered to carry out 180 hours of community
service by Mr Justice Laws following a plea bargain with the SFO's lawyers.
The Levitt Group, which collapsed in December 1990, attrac-ted celebrities
such as former athlete Mr Sebastian Coe, now an MP, and entertainer Adam
Faith to act as directors of its subsidiaries. Its most famous individual
loser was the writer Mr Frederick Forsyth, who lost Pounds 900,000.
The sentence imposed on Mr Levitt, following a three-year investigation and
prosecution by the SFO, provoked widespread anger among both investors who
lost money in the collapse of the Levitt Group and City regulators.
The SFO defended its decision not to proceed with 21 charges against Mr
Levitt and Mr Mark Reed, the group's former managing director, a week into
the trial. These included obtaining property and services by deception,
forgery, false accounting and making misleading statements.
In return, the two men pleaded guilty to a severely limited part of the
indictment against them - a fraudulent trading charge involving the
deception of Fimbra, the self-regulatory body for financial advisers.
The SFO yesterday denied this had been a misjudgment, saying that the
offence the two men pleaded guilty to - which carried a possible seven year
jail sentence - adequately reflected their criminality and that the trial
judge alone was responsible for deciding sentences. Passing sentence, Mr
Justice Laws said he could only sentence on the charges to which the two men
had pleaded guilty. These were comparable to breaches of the Financial
Services Act carrying a two-year sentence. Given their loss of reputations
and fortunes, community service orders were 'commensurate', he said.
In such cases the attorney-general can not appeal against a sentence on
grounds of leniency.
Afterwards a beaming Mr Levitt said he was 'a great believer in British
justice'. The bankrupt entrepreneur - who will now become a vacuum cleaner
salesman - planned to celebrate by getting drunk. 'I will have to borrow the
money first,' he added.
Fimbra said sentencing was a matter for the courts. However, Mr Jim Gaskin,
the Fimbra director of enforcement responsible for the Levitt case, admitted
there was considerable unhappiness at the outcome of the trial. 'Low
sentences for fraud give out the wrong signals to both those who suffer from
fraud and those who perpetrate it,' he said.
The outcome also caused dismay among lawyers acquainted with the case.
Concern centred on how an investigation and prosecution which cost millions
of pounds could end with sentences of community service orders. 'It looks
very bad. I feel ashamed,' said one lawyer as he left the courtroom. 'It's
extraordinary - a scandal,' said a QC who specialises in fraud cases. The
sentence was attacked by Labour front bench spokesperson Ms Marjorie Mowlam,
who said: 'The decision is an insult to many people who suffered at the
hands of Levitt.' One investor said: 'He (Mr Levitt) should pay for what he
has done.'
Mr Reed was ordered to do 120 hours of community service. A third defendant,
Mr Alan MacNamara, who admitted a charge of recklessly furnishing misleading
information to Fimbra, will be sentenced on Wednesday.
</TEXT>
