<HEADLINE>
FT  27 NOV 93 / UK Company News: Learmonth shares tumble on setback
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN CANE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Shares in Learmonth &amp; Burchett Management Systems, a USM-quoted computing
services company, lost more than a quarter of their value yesterday after
interim profits sharply below expectations.
Pre-tax profits were Pounds 201,000, 73 per cent lower than last time's
Pounds 753,000. The shares fell 60p to close at 163p.
Turnover increased by 22 per cent to Pounds 13.1m (Pounds 10.7m) and
earnings per share amounted to 1p (3.1p).
Mr Rainer Burchett, chairman, said the profits slide was the result of slow
trading conditions in the UK and a period of inactivity among the company's
agents in mainland Europe: 'Most of our new European business partners
decided to invest seriously in sales and marketing activity only after the
summer holiday period and we failed to anticipate the extent to which this
would cause a deferral of first-half sales,' he said.
He said the company's US subsidiary had shown rapid growth, trebling
software sales from Dollars 2.1m to Dollars 6.1m (Pounds 4.09m). The
Australian subsidiary had performed well, although below budget.
Mr Burchett said he expected significant improvement in the second half of
the year and that profits for the whole year would be broadly similar to
last year's Pounds 1.8m.
