<HEADLINE>
FT  27 NOV 93 / International Company News: OMI International stages
recovery with Pounds 237,000
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CATHERINE MILTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
OMI International, the electro-hydraulics, logistics and electro-optics
company, returned to pre-tax profits with Pounds 237,000 in the six months
to September 30, against losses of Pounds 2.69m in the comparable period.
Turnover fell to Pounds 17.8m (Pounds 20.3m). Forward Industries, acquired
five months ago, contributed sales of Pounds 3m but the figures lacked last
time's Pounds 3.75m contribution from some design businesses which had been
sold.
'I do not anticipate any real change in trading conditions over the second
half of this financial year,' said Mr Gil Williams, chairman.
The board declared a maintained interim dividend of 0.75p, uncovered by
earnings per share of 0.5p (6.1p losses), on the back of results slightly
ahead of expectations and as a measure of 'quiet optimism' about prospects.
Sales in the logistics services businesses fell due to lower spares support
activity, in spite of a 30 per cent increase in newer technology products.
Trading profits improved 17 per cent to Pounds 385,000 on sales down at
Pounds 6.1m (Pounds 6.45m).
The company said the design business was unlikely to make a loss in the
second half, but reported operating losses of Pounds 252,000 (Pounds
177,000) this time, on sales down at Pounds 4.58m (Pounds 6.27m).
Forward had performed well and the other manufacturing businesses were
healthy with profits for the division climbing to Pounds 652,000 (Pounds
504,000) on sales up at Pounds 4.12m (Pounds 3.81m).
Interest payable climbed to Pounds 242,000 (Pounds 96,000), including an
extra Pounds 100,000 for the loan taken out to cover the Forward
acquisition.
Net borrowings and finance leases rose to Pounds 6.64m (Pounds 2.59m) giving
gearing of 49.6 per cent, with the increase mainly attributable to Forward.
</TEXT>
